`,(0,n.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["If you rewind to our multi-threading example, you'll notice that we used a ",(0,n.jsx)(e.code,{children:"loop"})," in order to detect when our files were processed. It was simple: Loop infinitely until there is some content in the variable and then do something. We could have improved on that by breaking out of the loop if both files are read."]}),`
`,(0,n.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["An Async executor is the loop. Rust, by default, doesn't have any built-in executors. There is a number of Async run-times; ",(0,n.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://async.rs/",children:"async-std"})," and ",(0,n.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://tokio.rs/",children:"Tokio"})," being the most popular ones. The job of a run-time is to poll your async functions (",(0,n.jsx)(e.code,{children:"Future"}),"s) until they finally return a value."]}),`
`,(0,n.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["This ",(0,n.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://www.reddit.com/r/rust/comments/d1obg6/with_asyncawait_i_dont_get_what_runs_the_await/ezoxzjn/",children:"discussion"})," on Reddit has more details, but you can ignore the specifics for now."]}),`
